      <hedline>
        <hl1>Safeties Off</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Greenman letter on David Thomson's August 20 article on television remake of movie High Noon recalls seeing original in 1952 at army base in Korea (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The television remake of ''High Noon'' [''The Winding Road of the Western Hero'' by David Thomson, Aug. 20] reminded me of the circumstances under which I saw the original, early in 1952, at I Corps headquarters in Uijongbu, Korea. All men and officers had to carry their weapons at night, even when going to the movie tent.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The television remake of ''High Noon'' [''The Winding Road of the Western Hero'' by David Thomson, Aug. 20] reminded me of the circumstances under which I saw the original, early in 1952, at I Corps headquarters in Uijongbu, Korea. All men and officers had to carry their weapons at night, even when going to the movie tent.</p>
        <p>As the ex-cons approached the town by train, intent on killing the sheriff, the tension mounted. It was only a minute or two until high noon. I heard clicking sounds in the tent, as G.I.'s released the safety catches on their rifles. It was a rare moment in American movie history, when the audience was more heavily armed than the cast.</p>
        <p>ROBERT GREENMAN  Wappingers Falls, N.Y.</p>
        <p>'HIGH NOON'</p>
      </block>
